1)Why Binary Search is Not Suitable for Linked Lists?
  Binary Search is generally not suitable for Linked Lists because it requires direct access to the middle element.
  In a linked list, there is no index-based access, so we must traverse nodes sequentially to find the middle element.
  Finding the middle node takes O(n) time, which increases the overall complexity.
  Therefore, Binary Search loses its advantage and linear search is often preferred for linked lists.

  =>Can Binary Search be implemented on a Linked List?
  Yes, it can be implemented using slow and fast pointers to find the middle node,
  but it is inefficient because finding the middle node takes O(n) time.
  Therefore, the overall performance is worse than Binary Search on arrays.

  =>Is linear search is often preferred for linked lists?
  Yes, linear search is often preferred for linked lists because linked lists do not provide direct access to elements by index.
  To access any node, we must traverse from the head node sequentially.
  Binary search is inefficient because finding the middle element itself requires traversal.
  Therefore, linear search with O(n) time complexity is generally the preferred searching technique for linked lists.

2)How will you detect a cycle in a Linked List without using extra space?
  the most common answer is Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm (Slow and Fast Pointer).
  We use two pointers:
  Slow pointer moves one step at a time.
  Fast pointer moves two steps at a time.
  If there is no cycle, the fast pointer will reach null.
  If a cycle exists, the fast pointer will eventually meet the slow pointer inside the cycle.
  This approach does not use any extra data structure like HashSet.
  Time Complexity: O(n)
  Space Complexity: O(1)

  =>Why do slow and fast pointers meet if a cycle exists?
  Because the fast pointer moves faster than the slow pointer.
  Once both enter the cycle, the fast pointer keeps gaining on the slow pointer and will eventually catch up, causing them to meet.

3)Stack and queue.
  Stack and Queue are both linear data structures used to store and manage data, but they differ in the order in which elements are processed.
  Stack
  Stack follows the LIFO (Last In, First Out) principle.
  The last element inserted is the first element removed.
  Main operations:
  push() → Insert element
  pop() → Remove element
  peek() → View top element
  Example:
  Push: 10, 20, 30

  Top
   |
  30
  20
  10

  Pop() => 30

  Queue
  Queue follows the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle.
  The first element inserted is the first element removed.
  Main operations:
  offer()/add() → Insert element
  poll()/remove() → Remove element
  peek() → View front element
  Example:
  Front          Rear
    |              |
   10 -> 20 -> 30

  Poll() => 10

4)Can you tell me the difference between full, complete, and perfect binary tree?
 1. Full Binary Tree
 A Full Binary Tree is a tree where every node has either 0 or 2 children. No node can have only one child.

 Example:

         1
        / \
       2   3
      / \
     4   5

 ✅ Valid (every node has either 0 or 2 children)

 2. Complete Binary Tree
 A Complete Binary Tree is a tree where:
 All levels are completely filled except possibly the last level.
 Nodes in the last level are filled from left to right.

 Example:

         1
        / \
       2   3
      / \  /
     4  5 6

 ✅ Valid Complete Binary Tree

 3. Perfect Binary Tree
 A Perfect Binary Tree is a tree where:
 All internal nodes have exactly 2 children.
 All leaf nodes are at the same level.
 Every level is completely filled.

 Example:

           1
         /   \
        2     3
       / \   / \
      4  5  6  7

 ✅ Perfect Binary Tree

 One-Line Memory Trick
 Full → No node has only one child.
 Complete → Fill levels left to right.
 Perfect → Full + Complete + all leaves at the same level.

 =>Is every Perfect Binary Tree also Full and Complete?
  Yes. A Perfect Binary Tree satisfies the conditions of both a Full Binary Tree and a Complete Binary Tree.

  =>Is every Complete Binary Tree a Full Binary Tree?
  Answer: No. A Complete Binary Tree may contain nodes with only one child on the last level.

5)What Causes a Hash Collision?
  A hash collision occurs when two different keys generate the same hash value (same bucket/index) in a hash-based data structure such as a HashMap.

  Example
  Suppose the hash function produces:
  Key: "ABC" -> Hash Value: 5
  Key: "XYZ" -> Hash Value: 5
  Even though the keys are different, both map to the same bucket (5). This is called a hash collision.

  Why Do Hash Collisions Occur?
  The number of possible keys is very large.
  The number of buckets in a HashMap is limited.
  Different objects can produce the same hash value.
  A poorly implemented hashCode() method can increase collisions.

  =>Can two different objects have the same hashCode()?
  Yes. Two different objects can have the same hashCode(). This causes a hash collision.
  HashMap then uses both hashCode() and equals() to identify the correct key.

6)can a graph have multiple spanning trees?
  Yes, a graph can have multiple spanning trees.

  What is a Spanning Tree?
  A spanning tree is a subgraph that:
  Includes all vertices of the graph.
  Has no cycles.
  Contains exactly V - 1 edges (where V is the number of vertices).
  Keeps all vertices connected.
  Example

  Consider the graph:

      A
     / \
    B---C

  Edges: AB, BC, AC

  Possible spanning trees:

  Tree 1

  A
  |
  B
  |
  C

  Edges: AB, BC

  Tree 2

  A
  |
  C
  |
  B

  Edges: AC, BC

  Tree 3

  B
  |
  A
  |
  C

  Edges: AB, AC

  So this graph has 3 different spanning trees.

  Interview Answer (6–7 Lines)
  Yes, a connected graph can have multiple spanning trees. A spanning tree is a connected subgraph that includes all vertices and contains no cycles.
  To create a spanning tree, we remove enough edges to eliminate cycles while keeping all vertices connected.
  Different combinations of edge removals can produce different spanning trees. A graph with cycles usually has multiple spanning trees,
  whereas a graph that is already a tree has exactly one spanning tree.

  =>How many spanning trees does a tree graph have?
    Exactly one. Since a tree already has no cycles and contains V - 1 edges, removing any edge would disconnect the graph.

7)Why Can't We Use Binary Search on Unsorted Data?
  Binary Search works only on sorted data because it decides whether to search the left half or the right half based on comparisons with the middle element.

  For example, in a sorted array:
  10 20 30 40 50 60 70

  If we search for 60:
  Middle element = 40
  Since 60 > 40, we know the element can only be on the right side.
  We safely discard the left half.

  However, in an unsorted array:
  30 10 60 20 50 40 70
  If the middle element is 20, we cannot determine whether 60 is on the left or right side. Discarding half of the array may cause us to miss the target.

8)When we will use merge short over quick short
  Merge Sort is preferred when stable sorting is required, when working with linked lists, or when guaranteed O(n log n) performance is needed.
  It is also widely used for external sorting of large datasets stored on disk.
  Quick Sort is usually faster for arrays in memory and uses less extra space, but its worst-case time complexity is O(n²).
  Therefore, if stability and predictable performance are important, Merge Sort is a better choice.
  If memory efficiency and average-case speed are more important, Quick Sort is generally preferred.

  Easy Way to Remember
  Merge Sort → Stable, Linked Lists, Guaranteed Performance.
  Quick Sort → Faster in practice, Less Memory, Arrays.


Problem
Find the element with the second highest occurrence (frequency) in a list.

Example
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5);
Frequency:
1 -> 1
2 -> 2
3 -> 3
4 -> 4  (highest)
5 -> 2

Second highest occurrence = 3
Element = 3

import java.util.*;

public class SecondHighestFrequency {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(
                1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5);

        Map<Integer, Integer> freqMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (Integer num : list) {
            freqMap.put(num, freqMap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        int highest = 0;
        int secondHighest = 0;
        Integer result = null;

        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : freqMap.entrySet()) {

            int freq = entry.getValue();

            if (freq > highest) {
                secondHighest = highest;
                highest = freq;
            } else if (freq > secondHighest && freq < highest) {
                secondHighest = freq;
            }
        }

        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : freqMap.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() == secondHighest) {
                result = entry.getKey();
                break;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Element with second highest occurrence: " + result);
        System.out.println("Frequency: " + secondHighest);
    }
}
